WEBVTT

00:06.441 --> 00:09.357
- Previously on "Dirty John:
The Betty Broderick Story"...

00:09.400 --> 00:11.272
- The only thing an attorney
ever did for me was lose.

00:11.315 --> 00:13.665
- Will you at least let me
help you try not to lose?

00:13.709 --> 00:16.059
- Could you have come across
Betty's China?

00:16.103 --> 00:17.408
If you give the China back,

00:17.452 --> 00:19.845
it could be
a little olive branch.

00:19.889 --> 00:22.022
- Or I could break it.

00:22.065 --> 00:23.501
I mean,
that's what she would do.

00:23.545 --> 00:26.243
- I find that Mr. Broderick
will retain sole custody.

00:26.287 --> 00:28.767
Mrs. Broderick is awarded
formal visitation rights

00:28.811 --> 00:31.379
on alternating holidays
and weekends.

00:31.422 --> 00:33.946
- I don't want to see you
or the whore

00:33.990 --> 00:35.252
or the slums where you live

00:35.296 --> 00:36.601
or any
of your bullshit anymore.

00:36.645 --> 00:39.256
I close my eyes,
and I see you and the whore

00:39.300 --> 00:40.910
doing all your
wonderful things.

00:40.953 --> 00:42.912
You made my life a nightmare.

00:42.955 --> 00:45.654
You're gonna be real sorry.

00:46.394 --> 00:50.833
- California civil jury
instruction number 1707.

00:50.876 --> 00:54.141
"An opinion may be considered
a statement of fact

00:54.184 --> 00:57.883
if said opinion
suggests that facts exist."

00:57.927 --> 01:00.103
Now, in deciding this issue,
you should consider whether

01:00.147 --> 01:02.540
the average listener
would conclude,

01:02.584 --> 01:04.847
from the language
of a statement and its context,

01:04.890 --> 01:09.156
that the person was making
a statement of fact.

01:09.199 --> 01:10.809
Here's a statement of fact.

01:10.853 --> 01:14.248
Very few people
understand what I just said,

01:14.291 --> 01:15.553
including myself.

01:15.597 --> 01:18.513
[laughter]

01:18.556 --> 01:21.124
- Well, also, really,
how many wine tastings

01:21.168 --> 01:22.734
are you gonna want to do?
- True.

01:22.778 --> 01:24.649
- Yeah, and you can't count
on the weather.

01:24.693 --> 01:25.607
- Yeah.

01:25.650 --> 01:27.739
- So then what does that leave?

01:27.783 --> 01:30.220
Just Mexico, right?

01:30.264 --> 01:33.093
Cabo or Acapulco.

01:33.136 --> 01:36.879
both: Cabo.
[laughter]

01:38.576 --> 01:40.056
- Where's Betty think
we should go?

01:40.100 --> 01:41.492
- Nancy.

01:41.536 --> 01:43.625
- You should ask her.
She might tell you.

01:43.668 --> 01:44.887
- Can you imagine

01:44.930 --> 01:47.107
the message she would leave
if you did that?

01:47.150 --> 01:49.152
- Wait,
she went to jail for it,

01:49.196 --> 01:51.763
but she's still
leaving you messages?

01:51.807 --> 01:53.591
- [laughs]

01:53.635 --> 01:56.333
- What happens
when two people

01:56.377 --> 01:59.031
perceive the same thing
differently?

01:59.075 --> 02:00.511
If your perception
of a given event

02:00.555 --> 02:02.774
doesn't line up with mine,

02:02.818 --> 02:05.603
whose perception
of that event is true?

02:05.647 --> 02:07.170
Now, we're not talking
about people who are

02:07.214 --> 02:09.172
clinically
mentally compromised.

02:09.216 --> 02:12.393
Those individuals need medical
and psychological treatment,

02:12.436 --> 02:14.743
not legal counsel.

02:14.786 --> 02:15.874
- "Is anybody home?

02:15.918 --> 02:17.920
"Who was that
who picked up earlier?

02:17.963 --> 02:20.009
"Maybe it was the whore.

02:20.052 --> 02:21.706
"She's supposed to answer
the phone at the office

02:21.750 --> 02:23.447
"and spread her legs
at the house.

02:23.491 --> 02:25.362
Why can't she
get that straight?"

02:25.406 --> 02:26.755
- Oh!
- [laughs]

02:26.798 --> 02:29.323
- Whether they've been
injured or sued

02:29.366 --> 02:31.063
or charged with a crime,

02:31.107 --> 02:35.067
your clients' interest
must be your ultimate concern.

02:35.111 --> 02:38.375
And their perception of reality
is the one that matters.

02:38.419 --> 02:41.900
So, as their lawyer,
you need to uncover facts

02:41.944 --> 02:43.989
that support that perception,

02:44.033 --> 02:47.471
because your client's
perception is their truth.

02:47.515 --> 02:49.778
And serving them means
doing your utmost to show

02:49.821 --> 02:53.608
that their truth
represents the ultimate truth.

02:53.651 --> 02:56.654
- "She has ruined six lives,
and hers was never anything

02:56.698 --> 02:58.308
that counted to anyone anyway,
so..."

02:58.352 --> 03:00.049
- Oh, my God.
- [gasps]

03:00.092 --> 03:02.312
- "She had nothing to lose--
has nothing to lose.

03:02.356 --> 03:04.096
Once a whore,
always a whore."

03:04.140 --> 03:05.489
- [laughs]

03:05.533 --> 03:08.623
- How have you dealt with this?

03:08.666 --> 03:09.798
- She's a witch.

03:09.841 --> 03:12.061
- It's unbelievable.
- An evil witch.

03:12.104 --> 03:13.497
- She needs to go back to jail.

03:13.541 --> 03:15.499
- ♪ Goin' to the chapel

03:15.543 --> 03:20.112
♪ And I'm gonna get married

03:20.156 --> 03:23.115
♪ Goin' to the chapel
of love ♪

03:23.159 --> 03:24.769
[laughter]

03:24.813 --> 03:25.814
Cabo.

03:25.857 --> 03:28.686
all: Cabo.
- It's gotta be Cabo.

03:28.730 --> 03:31.863
- There are those who consider
truth to be universal.

03:31.907 --> 03:33.778
Those people
are not trial lawyers.

03:33.822 --> 03:35.302
Or--scratch that.

03:35.345 --> 03:37.434
Those people are not
successful trial lawyers.

03:37.478 --> 03:39.001
[light laughs]

03:39.044 --> 03:42.787
Successful trial lawyers are
absolutely seekers of truth.

03:42.831 --> 03:46.835
They are seekers of it,
but more important than that,

03:46.878 --> 03:49.925
they are the ones
who define what truth is.

03:49.968 --> 03:52.884
[dramatic music]

03:52.928 --> 03:57.846
♪

03:57.889 --> 04:02.024
- The humiliations
I put up with,

04:02.067 --> 04:05.245
the stories
I heard about myself.

04:07.682 --> 04:11.251
No Christmas,
no birthdays with my kids.

04:13.644 --> 04:17.082
Everything I suffered,
everything I didn't react to,

04:17.126 --> 04:21.217
I didn't stand up for,
I didn't fight for.

04:21.261 --> 04:23.741
You know Alice
"Through the Looking-Glass"?

04:23.785 --> 04:26.962
You know that dark tunnel
she fell down?

04:29.138 --> 04:32.272
That's you.

04:36.363 --> 04:39.322
[dark music]

04:39.366 --> 04:45.459
♪

04:47.548 --> 04:49.376
- In the backyard where?
At that house?

04:49.419 --> 04:50.377
- Yeah.
- How many people?

04:50.420 --> 04:52.379
More than 100?
- I think so.

04:52.422 --> 04:53.989
- What's she wearing?
Is she wearing white?

04:54.032 --> 04:56.557
- Yes.
- [laughs]

04:56.600 --> 04:58.950
[inhales]

04:58.994 --> 05:00.561
What's he wearing?

05:00.604 --> 05:02.389
- Um, a gray suit

05:02.432 --> 05:03.825
that's, like,
long in the back,

05:03.868 --> 05:05.305
with a gray vest.

05:05.348 --> 05:07.437
- A morning coat?

05:07.481 --> 05:08.873
Morning dress?

05:08.917 --> 05:11.093
It's exactly what he was
supposed to wear

05:11.136 --> 05:13.487
to our wedding,
but he refused.

05:13.530 --> 05:15.532
He said he didn't
want to wear rented clothes.

05:15.576 --> 05:17.969
My mother was humiliated.

05:20.320 --> 05:22.887
[scoffs]

05:22.931 --> 05:24.106
Where's the honeymoon?

05:24.149 --> 05:27.544
- Like, Caribbean somewhere.

05:27.588 --> 05:29.372
- Getting married in April,

05:29.416 --> 05:30.939
in morning dress,
taking her to the Caribbean.

05:30.982 --> 05:32.549
Is there anything
about this that Dan Broderick

05:32.593 --> 05:35.422
didn't already do with me,
or refuse to do?

05:35.465 --> 05:38.468
- You guys got married
in a church.

05:39.861 --> 05:41.384
- Jesus.

05:43.212 --> 05:45.693
He didn't think
I wouldn't find out?

05:45.736 --> 05:48.130
About the clothes and the--

05:48.173 --> 05:50.828
He knew I would.
He could pick any month,

05:50.872 --> 05:52.917
any clothes, any place.

05:52.961 --> 05:55.180
Why those?
- Okay, Mom, I have to go.

05:55.224 --> 05:56.181
Bye.

05:56.225 --> 05:58.445
[click, dial tone]

05:58.488 --> 06:00.490
- [sighs]

06:03.450 --> 06:05.843
- Throw to second is high.
- And it's caught.

06:05.887 --> 06:07.367
Out by a mile.

06:07.410 --> 06:09.847
- Mom.
- Hey, shake it off.

06:11.545 --> 06:13.329
- Next in the lineup
is Kirk Gibson.

06:13.373 --> 06:16.332
- Ooh, Kirk Gibson.
Kirk Gibson is up.

06:16.376 --> 06:17.855
He plays for the Dodgers,
right?

06:17.899 --> 06:19.161
- Yeah, yeah.
He's really good.

06:19.204 --> 06:21.250
- Two outs.
Here we go.

06:22.686 --> 06:25.472
- To deep center field,
and no one is there!

06:25.515 --> 06:27.256
- Oh, come on, this is stupid.
- And the third baseman scores!

06:27.299 --> 06:28.823
Whoo-hoo!
- I hate this.

06:28.866 --> 06:30.477
[loud thud]

06:31.739 --> 06:33.480
- Hey, no, no!
Don't move.

06:33.523 --> 06:35.482
Stand back.

06:35.525 --> 06:38.485
[dramatic music]

06:38.528 --> 06:43.359
♪

06:43.403 --> 06:44.795
I have to show
you guys something,

06:44.839 --> 06:47.624
but you have to promise
you'll never, ever touch it.

06:47.668 --> 06:50.105
I love how I have to
get you back by 4:00

06:50.148 --> 06:52.847
just to get leave you
with a housekeeper.

06:52.890 --> 06:55.110
Anthony Broderick.

06:55.153 --> 06:58.026
- Thanks.
- What did it look like, again?

06:58.069 --> 07:00.420
- Okay, it's a blue dress

07:00.463 --> 07:03.771
with slippery fabric
and a belt.

07:03.814 --> 07:05.294
- Okay.
- And if it's not

07:05.337 --> 07:08.340
in Tracy's room, that means
she took it to Colorado.

07:08.384 --> 07:09.429
- Okay.

07:12.127 --> 07:13.215
- Hey, Gladys.
- Hi, boys.

07:13.258 --> 07:16.044
Did you have a nice time?

07:26.924 --> 07:29.840
[lightly edgy music]

07:29.884 --> 07:37.021
♪

07:38.240 --> 07:39.415
