07:39.459 --> 07:46.378
♪

07:54.517 --> 08:01.437
♪

08:07.791 --> 08:10.011
- Found it.

08:10.054 --> 08:12.579
- Thank you, honey.
- Mm-hmm.

08:13.536 --> 08:16.060
- I love you.
- Love you.

08:16.104 --> 08:17.409
- Okay.

08:17.453 --> 08:20.543
[lightly edgy music continues]

08:20.587 --> 08:23.372
♪

08:23.415 --> 08:25.200
- This was the only place
that had enough tables

08:25.243 --> 08:26.331
to rent that weekend.

08:26.375 --> 08:27.811
- And suddenly,
now they don't?

08:27.855 --> 08:29.465
- Well, they have the number
of tables that we need,

08:29.509 --> 08:31.467
but for six and not for eight.

08:31.511 --> 08:34.731
- Just rejigger everyone
into tables of six.

08:34.775 --> 08:36.080
- Yeah.
- What?

08:36.124 --> 08:37.995
We just throw the place cards
up in the air,

08:38.039 --> 08:40.171
and wherever they fall,
divide by six.

08:40.215 --> 08:42.304
- I'll throw you
up in there air.

08:42.347 --> 08:44.524
They are your friends
and colleagues.

08:44.567 --> 08:46.743
Let me show you how
it has been carefully sorted

08:46.787 --> 08:49.267
into groups of eight
that can't just be rejiggered.

08:49.311 --> 08:51.313
- Can we order pizza?
- Uh, you know what?

08:51.356 --> 08:54.011
I think Linda has plans
for the evening for dinner.

08:54.055 --> 08:55.230
- What?
- I don't know.

08:55.273 --> 08:56.666
We should ask her.
- Um, it's not there.

08:56.710 --> 08:57.754
Have you seen it?

08:57.798 --> 08:59.321
- Not where?
Seen what?

08:59.364 --> 09:00.714
- The invite list, the list.

09:00.757 --> 09:02.585
It was next to the phone.
I was talking to Amelia.

09:02.629 --> 09:04.413
- I haven't seen it.
You sure you left it there?

09:04.456 --> 09:05.283
- [sighs]

09:05.327 --> 09:07.329
- Maybe it got moved when

09:07.372 --> 09:09.853
the downstairs
was being vacuumed.

09:09.897 --> 09:11.551
- She brought you home.

09:14.205 --> 09:16.425
Did she come in the house?

09:16.468 --> 09:18.993
She's not allowed to do that.
You are not allowed

09:19.036 --> 09:20.429
to let her--
- Linda.

09:20.472 --> 09:22.083
- What? It was probably like
Christmas when she saw it.

09:22.126 --> 09:23.388
And what she's gonna do,
burn it?

09:23.432 --> 09:24.825
- Why don't you guys
go start your homework?

09:24.868 --> 09:25.956
What do you want on your pizza?

09:26.000 --> 09:27.654
- Same as--
- Large. Half meatball.

09:27.697 --> 09:29.612
- Good call.

09:32.702 --> 09:35.618
Okay, don't worry about it.
She's not gonna burn it.

09:35.662 --> 09:37.185
And if she has it--
- Oh, she does.

09:37.228 --> 09:38.490
- She'd be thrilled about it,
okay?

09:38.534 --> 09:40.623
She'd probably keep it
forever if we let her,

09:40.667 --> 09:42.190
which we won't.

09:42.233 --> 09:44.845
- Why won't she
just leave us alone?

09:44.888 --> 09:47.021
- We'll get it back.

09:47.064 --> 09:48.588
- How?

09:50.067 --> 09:52.026
[answering machine beep]

09:52.069 --> 09:54.550
- Hi, Mo and Joanna.
It's Betty.

09:54.594 --> 09:56.857
Just in case you were
planning on going to Dan's

09:56.900 --> 09:58.685
stupid shitty wedding
to his office girl,

09:58.728 --> 10:03.385
I just felt like you should
know you're not invited.

10:03.428 --> 10:07.432
Anyway, I hope you're well.
Bye!

10:09.086 --> 10:10.479
[dialing]

10:13.264 --> 10:14.744
- Where's Anthony?

10:14.788 --> 10:16.746
- Bathtub, still.

10:16.790 --> 10:20.402
- Hey. Linda's really sorry.

10:20.445 --> 10:24.406
It's hard
putting together a wedding.

10:24.449 --> 10:26.321
A bride needs everything
to be perfect.

10:26.364 --> 10:28.802
If something goes wrong,
she ends up yelling at people,

10:28.845 --> 10:31.108
even if it's not their fault.

10:34.024 --> 10:35.765
- Can I tell you something?

10:35.809 --> 10:38.289
- About weddings?

10:38.333 --> 10:41.771
- Mom has a gun.

10:41.815 --> 10:43.425
- Yeah?

10:43.468 --> 10:45.079
- It's in her room.

10:45.122 --> 10:47.298
She told us never to touch it,

10:47.342 --> 10:49.431
but she also told us
that she'd take us to shoot it

10:49.474 --> 10:52.564
so we know why
never to touch it.

10:52.608 --> 10:55.263
Is it okay that she has it?

10:55.306 --> 10:58.092
- Well, she's not
keeping it a secret.

10:58.135 --> 11:00.007
She wanted you to tell me.

11:00.050 --> 11:02.270
That's why she
showed it to you guys.

11:02.313 --> 11:05.447
She wants me to know.

11:11.583 --> 11:14.021
- She said that she needs it.

11:14.064 --> 11:18.112
'Cause she's living alone now,
and she's scared.

11:18.155 --> 11:21.071
[dark music]

11:21.115 --> 11:26.163
♪

11:27.469 --> 11:30.602
[footsteps approach]

11:30.646 --> 11:33.736
- Mardi Gras.
Since Easter's in March.

11:33.780 --> 11:35.999
- I love it.
Oh, phone's for you.

11:36.043 --> 11:38.567
Don't worry,
not your kids' school.

11:38.610 --> 11:40.177
- Okay.

11:46.618 --> 11:48.708
This is Betty.

11:48.751 --> 11:51.188
Hello?

11:51.232 --> 11:53.451
Hello?

11:53.495 --> 11:55.192
Nobody's there.

11:56.803 --> 11:59.719
[suspenseful music]

11:59.762 --> 12:06.813
♪

12:27.877 --> 12:35.015
♪

12:36.538 --> 12:38.453
- [laughs]

12:44.676 --> 12:51.771
♪

13:02.216 --> 13:04.044
- Oh, is Mrs. Broderick here?

13:04.087 --> 13:06.786
- Uh, no.
She isn't.

13:06.829 --> 13:08.222
She's supposed to be
meeting with you?

13:08.265 --> 13:10.050
- She leaves the door unlocked
when she's at work.

13:10.093 --> 13:11.747
Are you her daughter?
- No, I'm her friend.

13:11.791 --> 13:13.444
I was just
picking something up.

13:13.488 --> 13:15.229
I really have to run.

13:27.676 --> 13:30.113
- Smells nice in here.
Lemony.

13:30.157 --> 13:32.376
- There's messages
on the machine.

13:33.900 --> 13:35.684
Oh, I found the earring.

13:35.727 --> 13:38.121
I put it in the dish
on your night table.

13:38.165 --> 13:41.385
Also,
a girl was here when I came.

13:41.429 --> 13:42.909
- Which one?

13:42.952 --> 13:46.521
Tracy's the brunette
and Jen's the blonde.

13:46.564 --> 13:49.480
- Young blonde,
but one of their friends maybe.

13:49.524 --> 13:52.657
She said friend.
She came to pick something up.

13:52.701 --> 13:54.442
What?
What did she pick up?

13:56.487 --> 13:59.403
[dramatic music]

13:59.447 --> 14:06.410
♪

14:06.454 --> 14:09.109
The notebook, my notebook
that's always right here...

14:09.152 --> 14:10.893
Did you move it?
- No.

14:10.937 --> 14:13.200
- Where is it?
It's always right here.

14:13.243 --> 14:14.854
- I don't--

14:15.942 --> 14:17.247
- You won't even look at it?

14:17.291 --> 14:18.727
- What's in it
doesn't matter.

14:18.770 --> 14:21.469
What matters is that you
went into her house to get it.

14:21.512 --> 14:22.949
You broke into
and entered her house.

14:22.992 --> 14:24.385
- The door was unlocked.

14:24.428 --> 14:26.517
- Fine, the door was unlocked,
so you trespassed.

14:26.561 --> 14:28.389
You trespassed
and stole her property.

14:28.432 --> 14:30.347
- Like she has done to us
so many times.

14:30.391 --> 14:32.262
- Exactly.
That's what she does,

14:32.306 --> 14:35.352
not what we do.
We do not do that.

14:37.398 --> 14:40.096
- "I have nowhere to turn.
I am desperate.

14:40.140 --> 14:42.142
"If this is the way
domestic disputes

14:42.185 --> 14:43.883
"are settled in the courts,

14:43.926 --> 14:45.362
is there any wonder
there are so many murders?"

14:45.406 --> 14:46.755
- Just put it back
where you found it.

14:46.798 --> 14:47.843
- What? How?

14:47.887 --> 14:50.933
- I don't care.
Just do it.

14:53.631 --> 14:55.633
- What if I'd been scheduled
to work this afternoon?

14:55.677 --> 14:57.592
What if I hadn't listened
to the machine?

14:57.635 --> 15:00.029
A 4:00 hearing?
That leaves three hours

15:00.073 --> 15:01.813
to get here, to get you here,
or otherwise what?

15:01.857 --> 15:03.380
I go back to jail?

15:03.424 --> 15:04.816
- Did you?

15:04.860 --> 15:05.905
- Did I what?

15:05.948 --> 15:07.167
- Did you take it, Betty?

15:07.210 --> 15:09.647
The list.
Their wedding list.

15:09.691 --> 15:11.301
- Why would I want--

15:11.345 --> 15:12.868
I don't even know
what they're talking about.

15:12.912 --> 15:15.001
- Well, obviously,
they say you do.

15:15.044 --> 15:16.132
And if the judge
sides with them,

15:16.176 --> 15:18.308
he's going to sanction you.

15:18.352 --> 15:20.310
- Counsel.

15:22.356 --> 15:25.228
- Your Honor,
this accusation is baseless.

15:25.272 --> 15:28.014
My client says she does not
have the property in question.

15:28.057 --> 15:30.494
- This latest offense
is completely in line

15:30.538 --> 15:34.759
with a well-documented pattern
of behavior, Your Honor.

15:34.803 --> 15:36.109
- I know.

15:36.152 --> 15:38.981
Here's what's gonna happen.

15:39.025 --> 15:42.071
As requested,
I am ordering Mr. Broderick

15:42.115 --> 15:44.682
to withhold financial
support of Mrs. Broderick

15:44.726 --> 15:47.555
until she either produces
the list in question

15:47.598 --> 15:50.123
or puts forth
a plausible explanation

15:50.166 --> 15:52.342
as to where it might be.

15:52.386 --> 15:55.563
Ms. Anstead, prepare the order,
and I'll sign it.

15:55.606 --> 15:57.043
Thank you.

16:00.437 --> 16:02.613
- Please, Betty.

16:02.657 --> 16:05.573
What is going on?

16:28.204 --> 16:31.555
[ominous music]

16:31.599 --> 16:38.475
♪

16:41.217 --> 16:44.612
Linda: Skin a mess.
Nails bitten to blood.

16:44.655 --> 16:46.614
Weight never higher.

16:46.657 --> 16:49.051
So unhappy, so lonesome.

16:49.095 --> 16:50.835
Can't fit into any
of my nice clothes.

16:50.879 --> 16:54.274
Dan: I am madder than hell
at lying, cheating,

16:54.317 --> 16:56.363
scumbag Broderick.

16:56.406 --> 16:58.147
I have every right to be.

16:58.191 --> 17:00.062
It would be crazy
if I weren't.

17:00.106 --> 17:02.369
Linda: I am a very up...
Dan: [laughing]

17:02.412 --> 17:04.066
Linda: Forgiving,
friendly person.

17:04.110 --> 17:06.242
Dan: Oh!
- I try not to dwell on

17:06.286 --> 17:08.549
[echoing] disappointment.
[Dan laughing]

17:08.592 --> 17:10.420
I try not to dwell
on the past.

17:10.464 --> 17:12.074
[echoing, laughter]
I try not to dwell

17:12.118 --> 17:15.034
on the past.
[laughter]

17:17.732 --> 17:20.474
[dramatic music]

17:20.517 --> 17:27.611
♪

17:36.620 --> 17:38.100
- It's not hard to imagine

17:38.144 --> 17:40.494
that she would want to cause
trouble on the day.

17:40.537 --> 17:43.105
- Or before when everything
is being delivered and set up.

17:43.149 --> 17:44.846
She knows that
if she ruins any of this

17:44.889 --> 17:46.500
that we'll have to cancel.

17:46.543 --> 17:48.763
- We could go down Saturday
and come back Monday.

17:48.806 --> 17:51.331
- I don't know, Karen.
I don't think so.

17:51.374 --> 17:52.941
- Okay, all right.
Well, then what is something

17:52.984 --> 17:56.118
we could do for the day?
Like a nice drive?

17:56.162 --> 17:57.902
- But she hasn't specifically
told anyone about

17:57.946 --> 17:59.600
how she might be planning
to disrupt the ceremony?

17:59.643 --> 18:00.818
- Not specifically.

18:00.862 --> 18:02.385
- Just that a lot of people
have told us

18:02.429 --> 18:04.431
that she's joked
about shooting us.

18:04.474 --> 18:07.521
- I was thinking
about buying a watch.

18:07.564 --> 18:11.090
A really gorgeous,
diamond bezel thing.

18:12.482 --> 18:14.441
And having it engraved.

18:14.484 --> 18:17.183
- Engraved with what?

18:17.226 --> 18:19.141
- The date.

18:19.185 --> 18:21.491
April 22, 1989.

18:21.535 --> 18:23.624
- And she owns a firearm,
you said?

18:23.667 --> 18:25.974
- We've heard that she does,
yeah.

18:26.017 --> 18:30.021
- And wh-who would it be for?

18:30.065 --> 18:32.067
- For me, Karen.

18:32.111 --> 18:34.156
It would be for me.

18:34.200 --> 18:35.549
- Well, I tell you what.

18:35.592 --> 18:37.899
I'll come over Sunday
at, like, 8:00, 8:30.

18:37.942 --> 18:40.684
We'll talk about that.
I'll see you Sunday.

18:40.728 --> 18:42.295
- See you Sunday.

18:42.338 --> 18:44.514
- What about a security system?
Have you given any thought--

18:44.558 --> 18:46.908
- Yeah, we thought about it.

18:48.431 --> 18:53.175
- You have a photo of your
ex-wife you can lend us, sir?

18:53.219 --> 18:57.048
- She's about yea high,
dark blonde, blue eyes,

18:57.092 --> 18:59.834
nothing a guy--or guys
like you couldn't handle.

18:59.877 --> 19:03.098
Just keep your eyes peeled
for a woman by herself

19:03.142 --> 19:06.188
who looks like
she doesn't belong.

19:06.232 --> 19:09.191
[ominous music]

19:09.235 --> 19:12.020
♪

19:12.063 --> 19:13.543
- She doesn't
want to leave town,

19:13.587 --> 19:15.937
and she wants to buy a watch

19:15.980 --> 19:18.505
and engrave it
with Dan's wedding date.

19:18.548 --> 19:20.855
- Ugh...all right.

19:20.898 --> 19:22.291
Which one do you want?

19:22.335 --> 19:24.337
- Are they both the same?
- They're different colors.

19:24.380 --> 19:25.773
- [sighs]

19:27.427 --> 19:31.474
- Okay,
so if you beep me 911,

19:31.518 --> 19:33.694
that means
you don't know where she is.

19:33.737 --> 19:36.218
- Oh, we're doing this now?

19:36.262 --> 19:38.916
Okay, fine, but I think we need
an intermediate number,

19:38.960 --> 19:42.224
a "don't panic, but" number,
a "heads up" number.

19:42.268 --> 19:43.138
- Which would be?

19:43.182 --> 19:44.661
- I don't know.
Maybe 666.

19:44.705 --> 19:48.187
And then 911 would be
the "I can't find her,

19:48.230 --> 19:50.319
"we don't know where she is,
maybe tell Dan

19:50.363 --> 19:53.235
she might be on her way
over there now" number.

19:53.279 --> 19:55.759
- [sighs]

19:57.587 --> 19:59.067
- Who offers
to host a bachelor party

19:59.110 --> 20:00.503
when they're allergic
to cigars?

20:00.547 --> 20:01.939
- Mmm.
- Who?

20:01.983 --> 20:03.680
Look at us,
standing in his backyard

20:03.724 --> 20:05.508
like goddamn derelicts.

20:05.552 --> 20:06.727
- [laughs]

20:06.770 --> 20:08.555
Pretty nice back here.

20:08.598 --> 20:10.078
- Really is.

20:10.121 --> 20:11.514
Nice little pond over there
and everything.

20:11.558 --> 20:12.863
- Mm.

20:12.907 --> 20:15.866
[muffled music, voices]

20:15.910 --> 20:20.001
- So there's gonna be
security at your wedding?

20:20.044 --> 20:23.309
- Just a couple of guys parked
in a car through the weekend.

20:23.352 --> 20:26.573
If I didn't tell you about it,
you'd never notice.

20:26.616 --> 20:28.923
- They gonna be armed?

20:28.966 --> 20:32.056
I've heard Betty's been
randomly talking to people

20:32.100 --> 20:34.407
about how she was an intramural
sharpshooter at college.

20:34.450 --> 20:35.799
- [laughs]

20:35.843 --> 20:37.671
- Or something.
I don't know.

20:37.714 --> 20:39.934
- That's what Betty does.
She talks.

20:39.977 --> 20:41.283
- And drives trucks
into your house.

20:41.327 --> 20:43.111
- [laughs]

20:43.154 --> 20:45.026
- Walt Mills said
he's not even coming.

20:45.069 --> 20:46.767
That if Betts has a hit list,
he's on it.

20:46.810 --> 20:49.857
- Just stop.
Everybody stop.

20:49.900 --> 20:51.772
The only thing Betty
cares about is money.

20:51.815 --> 20:54.470
That's the only thing
she has ever cared about.

20:54.514 --> 20:57.691
Without me,
there isn't any.

20:57.734 --> 20:59.780
She's not gonna kill
the golden goose, Richard.

20:59.823 --> 21:01.999
She just isn't.

21:02.043 --> 21:04.263
- [clears throat]
Well, there's more to you

21:04.306 --> 21:06.526
than money, Danny boy.

21:06.569 --> 21:08.745
- Is there?

21:08.789 --> 21:09.920
- Probably.
I mean--

21:09.964 --> 21:12.358
- [laughs]
- I assume.

21:12.401 --> 21:14.751
[men's muffled voices]

21:14.795 --> 21:17.711
[classical piano music]

21:17.754 --> 21:24.892
♪

21:33.640 --> 21:35.250
- Wow.

21:35.294 --> 21:38.079
How many buttons?

21:38.122 --> 21:39.515
- A lot.

21:39.559 --> 21:41.691
And all Irish lace.
- Mm.

21:42.692 --> 21:44.781
How much do I love
your mom's hat?

21:44.825 --> 21:47.915
- Me, too.

21:47.958 --> 21:49.612
She beautiful?

21:49.656 --> 21:51.832
- She is.

21:51.875 --> 21:54.878
I see where you get it.

22:01.624 --> 22:04.410
- Do you feel sorry for me?

22:04.453 --> 22:06.281
- No, I don't.

22:08.892 --> 22:11.068
You can do anything you want,
Betty.

22:11.112 --> 22:14.376
And now you're gonna have to.

22:14.420 --> 22:16.944
But I know you can.

22:18.859 --> 22:21.775
[upbeat music]

22:21.818 --> 22:27.389
♪

22:27.433 --> 22:28.608
- It's a mixtape.

22:28.651 --> 22:29.913
- That you made?

22:29.957 --> 22:31.437
- Uh, don't patronize me.

22:31.480 --> 22:34.527
- I know,
but...you made a mixtape?

22:34.570 --> 22:37.747
- Of songs that I like.
Now can I just please dance?

22:37.791 --> 22:39.793
- All right, fine,
but if you're dancing,

22:39.836 --> 22:41.969
I am dancing.

22:43.840 --> 22:46.800
- ♪ Says she loves me,
yes, yes, she does ♪

22:46.843 --> 22:49.193
♪

22:49.237 --> 22:52.153
♪ Gonna show me tonight,
yeah ♪

22:52.196 --> 22:55.243
♪ Hey, she got the way
to move me, Cherry ♪

22:55.286 --> 22:58.072
- ♪ She got the way
to groove me ♪

22:58.115 --> 23:00.944
♪ She got the way
to groove me ♪

23:00.988 --> 23:02.903
♪ She got the way
to groove me ♪

23:02.946 --> 23:04.861
- ♪ All right

23:04.905 --> 23:06.602
♪

23:06.646 --> 23:09.518
♪ Whee ha

23:09.562 --> 23:12.913
♪ Tell your mama, girl,
I can't stay long ♪

23:12.956 --> 23:15.263
[both squealing, laughing]

23:15.306 --> 23:18.745
♪ We got a thing
we gotta catch up on ♪

23:18.788 --> 23:21.051
♪

23:21.095 --> 23:24.098
♪ Mmm, oh you know
what I'm sayin'...♪

23:24.141 --> 23:27.841
- Born breech,
like the girls.

23:28.755 --> 23:30.844
7 pounds.

23:33.716 --> 23:35.805
[sniffles, clears throat]

23:37.067 --> 23:39.896
He lived for four days.

23:41.811 --> 23:43.857
- What was his name?

23:43.900 --> 23:46.207
- [cries]

23:51.995 --> 23:53.910
I thought about how the girls
were so young,

23:53.954 --> 23:58.001
they wouldn't even miss me,
and...

23:59.655 --> 24:04.834
Dan didn't seem to care whether
I was around or I wasn't.

24:07.184 --> 24:12.189
But then there started
to be California.

24:13.234 --> 24:15.541
The idea of California.

24:17.281 --> 24:18.979
Warm.

24:19.022 --> 24:21.808
Different.

24:21.851 --> 24:24.245
Better.

24:29.468 --> 24:32.471
And I didn't really
want to die.

24:37.301 --> 24:40.348
It's hard to kill hope
in people.

24:49.966 --> 24:52.534
Especially when they're young.

25:02.675 --> 25:05.547
- I know this day was hard.

25:05.591 --> 25:07.897
But it's over now.

25:07.941 --> 25:10.987
You never have to
go through it again.

25:25.524 --> 25:28.614
[ominous music]

25:28.657 --> 25:31.312
- Hi, we're back,
all tanned and rested.

25:31.355 --> 25:33.270
Please leave us a message.

25:35.708 --> 25:38.406
Hi, we're back,
all tanned and rested.

25:38.449 --> 25:39.886
Please leave us a message.

25:39.929 --> 25:42.149
[beep]

25:42.192 --> 25:45.413
The letter on the court order
states girlfriend.

25:45.456 --> 25:48.024
Get the girlfriend
off the machine.

25:48.068 --> 25:50.244
Now I'm your wife.

25:53.769 --> 25:55.684
- You know what you're doing.

25:55.728 --> 26:00.559
You are bright
and rational and stubborn.

26:00.602 --> 26:03.126
A strong-willed person.

26:03.170 --> 26:06.826
A loving person
who exhibits immaturity

26:06.869 --> 26:10.525
and poor judgment
under tremendous pressure.

26:10.569 --> 26:14.224
The state of your home,
your lifestyle,

26:14.268 --> 26:17.184
these things that you
say are hindering you--

26:17.227 --> 26:19.665
from my perspective
as your therapist,

26:19.708 --> 26:21.101
none of that is important.

26:21.144 --> 26:23.407
Your children live
in a luxurious lifestyle,

26:23.451 --> 26:25.409
and they are in crisis.

26:25.453 --> 26:28.456
Help them and yourself.

26:28.499 --> 26:32.547
I urge you, Betty,
get them home.

26:34.114 --> 26:37.726
- Everything I can afford is
either a condo or an apartment.

26:37.770 --> 26:40.294
I saw one condo
that could be okay.

26:40.337 --> 26:42.078
- How many bedrooms
does it have?

26:42.122 --> 26:45.255
- Two, but yours would be
smaller than your one here.

26:45.299 --> 26:48.476
You might have to...
think about bunk beds.

26:48.519 --> 26:49.651
- Cool!
- Henry and Charlie

26:49.695 --> 26:50.739
have bunk beds.

26:50.783 --> 26:52.349
- Really?
- Yeah.

26:52.393 --> 26:54.656
- That makes me feel better.

26:54.700 --> 26:56.310
All right, well, maybe
the next weekend you come,

26:56.353 --> 26:57.964
we can go looking.

26:58.007 --> 26:59.443
[TV playing]

26:59.487 --> 27:01.663
- Well, not the next one.

27:01.707 --> 27:03.578
Travel soccer
round robin is next one.

27:03.622 --> 27:05.754
- No, that's the 21st.

27:05.798 --> 27:08.627
- Dad takes us
to Indiana the 21st.

27:10.237 --> 27:11.673
You know?
The football game.

27:11.717 --> 27:14.284
Notre Dame and USC.

27:14.328 --> 27:16.678
- Who's "us"?

27:16.722 --> 27:20.987
- Well, us, Dad,

27:21.030 --> 27:23.032
Tracy, and Linda.

27:23.076 --> 27:24.947
[muffled]
And some of dad's friends

27:24.991 --> 27:27.297
are coming,
and their families, right?

27:27.341 --> 27:30.953
[TV music]

27:30.997 --> 27:33.477
- [chuckles]
Thank you.

27:33.521 --> 27:37.177
[game announcer over TV]

27:37.220 --> 27:38.961
- Good game.
Close game.

27:39.005 --> 27:41.877
- Mm, maybe.
But don't worry.

27:41.921 --> 27:43.749
We'll still be
taking home the Shillelagh.

27:43.792 --> 27:47.317
[background chatter]

27:47.361 --> 27:49.798
- I actually met my husband
in South Bend.

27:49.842 --> 27:51.234
'65.

27:51.278 --> 27:53.846
Notre Dame to the Shillelagh
that weekend, too.

27:53.889 --> 27:57.284
- '47.
At the Coliseum.

27:57.327 --> 27:59.765
[laughs]

27:59.808 --> 28:02.855
So we're both
Notre Dame wives.

28:05.335 --> 28:07.729
- I'm not.

28:07.773 --> 28:10.036
He left me for his secretary.

28:11.559 --> 28:13.996
That's who's there with him.

28:15.563 --> 28:18.044
With him and our kids
and our old friends.

28:21.569 --> 28:24.920
In the place where we met
and fell in love.

28:24.964 --> 28:27.531
- Ugh.

28:27.575 --> 28:31.057
I'm--is there...anything--

28:31.100 --> 28:35.975
- I just really wonder what
the other wives are thinking.

28:36.018 --> 28:38.978
Seeing this young thing
adoring Dan.

28:41.067 --> 28:42.982
And they're fortysomething,
too.

28:44.940 --> 28:49.205
Maybe their husbands
will go off, and...

28:49.249 --> 28:51.773
find some young chickie.

28:55.037 --> 28:57.953
Then they'll be gone,
just like me.

29:00.826 --> 29:03.567
- We finally saw it.
You have to tell Rich.

29:03.611 --> 29:05.221
- Oh, my God.
Did Frank cry?

29:05.265 --> 29:06.527
- Oh.
- No.

29:06.570 --> 29:08.572
But when the catcher
takes his mask off

29:08.616 --> 29:10.487
and it's
Kevin Costner's father,

29:10.531 --> 29:12.011
he dropped his ticket stub
on the floor

29:12.054 --> 29:13.229
and really, really
had to find it right away.

29:13.273 --> 29:15.928
- [laughs]

29:18.017 --> 29:19.627
Did you tell her
we'd be here?

29:19.670 --> 29:21.063
- I haven't seen her
in months.

29:21.107 --> 29:23.631
- Yeah,
maybe she saw one of our cars.

29:23.674 --> 29:24.937
- Hiya.

29:24.980 --> 29:27.243
I was driving by and suddenly,
I just knew

29:27.287 --> 29:30.203
you were all in here.

29:33.206 --> 29:34.729
- So how are you, Betty?

29:36.078 --> 29:38.124
- I was fine,
which isn't saying much.

29:38.167 --> 29:40.779
But, uh, then my lawyer
got a letter from the bastard

29:40.822 --> 29:42.041
saying they're going
to the Greek Isles

29:42.084 --> 29:44.086
with their friends,
and while they're gone,

29:44.130 --> 29:46.262
they would like
for my sons to be left

29:46.306 --> 29:48.351
with the housekeeper
during the week,

29:48.395 --> 29:50.658
and then on weekends
with a friend of the whore.

29:50.701 --> 29:52.747
So now I gotta go
beg a judge to let me

29:52.791 --> 29:54.357
be my sons' mother
for two weeks

29:54.401 --> 29:57.447
while their asshole father
isn't even in the country.

29:57.491 --> 30:00.537
I mean, can you believe
this cruel, phony,

30:00.581 --> 30:02.191
evil piece of shit?

30:02.235 --> 30:04.933
I mean, of course you can,
but can you?

30:07.893 --> 30:10.765
- Hi, we're back,
all tanned and rested.

30:10.809 --> 30:12.027
Please leave us a message.

30:12.071 --> 30:14.247
[answering machine beep]

30:14.290 --> 30:17.250
[uneasy music]

30:17.293 --> 30:19.469
♪

30:19.513 --> 30:23.343
[dialing]

30:23.386 --> 30:26.825
[line trilling]

30:26.868 --> 30:29.131
- "Dear Mr. Baxter,
I really wonder

30:29.175 --> 30:31.481
"whether you are serious
about trying to work out

30:31.525 --> 30:33.483
"a shared custody agreement.

30:33.527 --> 30:36.530
"There are many fundamental
problems with your proposal.

30:36.573 --> 30:38.358
"Unless you reorient yourself

30:38.401 --> 30:40.229
"to the point
of these negotiations,

30:40.273 --> 30:43.189
"that you initiated
I might add,

30:43.232 --> 30:45.931
[echoing] "I don't see any
reason to go into them.

30:45.974 --> 30:49.064
[voice becomes Dan's voice]
I suggest you try again."

30:49.108 --> 30:51.545
Enclosed please find
a verbatim transcript

30:51.588 --> 30:53.199
of just a few of this week's

30:53.242 --> 30:56.158
obscene answering machine
messages.

30:56.202 --> 30:59.335
You should know that since
Judge Russell's final ruling,

30:59.379 --> 31:01.903
your client has committed
at least 20 separate,

31:01.947 --> 31:04.123
similar acts of contempt.

31:06.255 --> 31:07.691
I am sure
that if we are forced

31:07.735 --> 31:09.171
to seek the court's assistance

31:09.215 --> 31:11.913
in enforcing the extant
restraining orders,

31:11.957 --> 31:14.916
another jail sentence
will be imposed.

31:14.960 --> 31:18.528
[ominous music]

31:18.572 --> 31:21.357
I find your client's actions
completely inconsistent

31:21.401 --> 31:24.012
with the contentions
of her psychotherapist

31:24.056 --> 31:25.361
that her emotional
disturbances

31:25.405 --> 31:27.798
and mental disease
are improving.

31:31.019 --> 31:33.674
The contrary
seems to be the case.

31:33.717 --> 31:37.721
♪

31:37.765 --> 31:39.375
- Well, what did he say?

31:39.419 --> 31:41.203
- He said it's too much

31:41.247 --> 31:44.685
and it was
the first place I saw

31:44.728 --> 31:47.383
and I should probably
have a roommate.

31:47.427 --> 31:49.908
- No. Take it.

31:49.951 --> 31:51.735
- [laughs]
- I'll pay for it.

31:51.779 --> 31:53.215
- Mom, no.

31:53.259 --> 31:56.740
Yes! The last place you lived
was like a jail cell.

31:56.784 --> 31:58.917
- Mm.

32:00.788 --> 32:02.572
Thanks, Mom.

32:02.616 --> 32:04.270
- You're welcome.

32:09.753 --> 32:11.190
Serves him right.

32:11.233 --> 32:13.148
Letting Linda Kolkena
tell you to give up your seat

32:13.192 --> 32:14.933
at a family function to her.

32:14.976 --> 32:17.196
- That's not what happened.

32:17.239 --> 32:19.415
- There were five people
and four chairs

32:19.459 --> 32:22.288
and you were in a chair,
and she asked you to move.

32:22.331 --> 32:23.811
- Okay--
- Is what you said.

32:23.854 --> 32:26.945
And your father just let her.
- Mom.

32:26.988 --> 32:29.469
I'm not gonna tell you
anything anymore.

32:29.512 --> 32:31.906
Serves you right.

32:31.950 --> 32:34.909
[dramatic music]

32:34.953 --> 32:38.957
♪

32:39.000 --> 32:41.089
[door opens, closes]

32:49.880 --> 32:51.404
- Around every corner,

32:51.447 --> 32:57.105
there is some gorgeous
tile staircase or cobblestones.

32:57.149 --> 32:58.498
I knew that none
of my pictures would turn out

32:58.541 --> 32:59.586
like the real thing,

32:59.629 --> 33:01.501
but I couldn't stop
taking pictures.

33:01.544 --> 33:03.111
Oh!
- Mm.

33:04.765 --> 33:07.898
- Everything was so
beautiful.

33:07.942 --> 33:10.336
I just wanted
to remember it all.

33:10.379 --> 33:12.338
- Well, I just want to talk
about where we're going next.

33:12.381 --> 33:13.556
both: Australia.

33:13.600 --> 33:14.818
- Australia!
- Yeah.

33:14.862 --> 33:16.124
- Wow!
- We don't have time

33:16.168 --> 33:17.604
to plan a trip
like that this year,

33:17.647 --> 33:19.649
or let alone go, but...

33:19.693 --> 33:20.824
- Maybe next year.
- Maybe.

33:20.868 --> 33:22.130
- Maybe, right?

33:22.174 --> 33:24.785
- What--what is that?

33:24.828 --> 33:25.873
Maybe what?

33:25.916 --> 33:27.222
- Uh...

33:27.266 --> 33:28.919
- Should I--
- Uh--

33:28.963 --> 33:32.836
- Maybe we...
won't be free

33:32.880 --> 33:35.578
to just pick up and go places,
is what.

33:35.622 --> 33:38.233
- And, um, why might that be?

33:39.582 --> 33:42.542
- Well, because, uh,
maybe

33:42.585 --> 33:45.110
there'll be a new member
of the family at some point

33:45.153 --> 33:47.590
that, uh,
we'll have to think about

33:47.634 --> 33:50.506
when we're making travel plans,
Celeste--that's why.

33:50.550 --> 33:52.204
Maybe!
- Ah...

33:54.075 --> 33:55.946
- All right,
let's order some food.

33:55.990 --> 33:58.036
[laughter]

33:58.079 --> 34:01.169
Okay, look,
I'm gonna get the tournedos,

34:01.213 --> 34:02.866
and then you get this--
what is it?

34:02.910 --> 34:04.172
The...
- The cassoulet.

34:04.216 --> 34:06.261
- The cassoulet.
And then we'll trade plates.

34:06.305 --> 34:07.828
- Yummy.
- You guys are plate-traders.

34:07.871 --> 34:09.351
- Oh, I like us
to trade plates.

34:09.395 --> 34:11.571
[muffled, fading]
- Only if...

34:11.614 --> 34:13.616
[continues indistinctly]

34:13.660 --> 34:15.749
[uneasy music]

34:15.792 --> 34:17.055
-I have a feeling
that this was

34:17.098 --> 34:19.709
his last year trick
or treating.

34:19.753 --> 34:21.146
[laughs]

34:21.189 --> 34:22.930
I mean,
I think that he still had fun

34:22.973 --> 34:24.714
but just the way
that he was talking about it.

34:24.758 --> 34:26.890
I think this time next year
it's gonna suddenly be

34:26.934 --> 34:28.544
beneath his dignity.

34:31.112 --> 34:33.549
Betty?
- Mm.

34:33.593 --> 34:36.248
- What'd the boys go as?

34:36.291 --> 34:39.860
- Uh, fireman and an Army man,
I think.

34:39.903 --> 34:41.470
Dan had said
I could take them out,

34:41.514 --> 34:43.516
but then they called,
and...

34:44.821 --> 34:47.781
Said they weren't coming.

34:47.824 --> 34:51.567
- That's, uh...

34:51.611 --> 34:53.439
I'm sorry.

34:54.788 --> 34:58.139
- Wasn't my first Halloween
without them.

35:02.317 --> 35:05.364
But you're right.
It was probably the last one.

35:12.849 --> 35:15.156
Is Linda pregnant?

35:17.027 --> 35:20.466
- How would I know that,
Betty?

35:20.509 --> 35:23.382
- Everyone knows
everything before me.

35:27.081 --> 35:29.344
- Here you go.

35:29.388 --> 35:32.956
John's so jealous
we're getting bunk beds.

35:33.000 --> 35:35.568
- Did he get
his cast off finally?

35:35.611 --> 35:39.006
- Yeah. His arm
was so white underneath.

35:39.049 --> 35:40.964
They're taking him
to Disneyland.

35:41.008 --> 35:42.270
- Who, his mom and dad?

35:42.314 --> 35:46.883
- Yeah. He asked me to go, too,
this weekend.

35:46.927 --> 35:48.711
But I said I couldn't
'cause if I went,

35:48.755 --> 35:50.670
I wouldn't get to see you.

35:54.456 --> 35:57.416
- [cries]

36:01.071 --> 36:03.117
[sniffling]

36:09.819 --> 36:13.171
I don't want to be
the reason you miss things.

36:13.214 --> 36:15.216
- Don't cry again, Mom.

36:15.260 --> 36:18.001
- No, I know.
I'm just tired.

36:18.045 --> 36:21.614
- Then you should
get some sleep.

36:36.890 --> 36:39.849
[dark music]

36:39.893 --> 36:46.769
♪

36:53.907 --> 37:00.783
♪

37:13.840 --> 37:16.712
[dark music continues]

37:16.756 --> 37:23.632
♪

37:46.960 --> 37:50.311
[uneasy electronic music]

37:50.355 --> 37:57.449
♪

38:22.082 --> 38:24.084
- There's a scene
in the "Superman" movie

38:24.127 --> 38:26.782
where he flies
around the Earth real fast,

38:26.826 --> 38:30.351
and he screams
this blood-curdling scream.

38:30.395 --> 38:32.875
♪

38:32.919 --> 38:36.836
That's what I felt like.

38:36.879 --> 38:43.103
♪

38:43.146 --> 38:45.584
Standing up and doing
a primal scream so loud

38:45.627 --> 38:49.762
the whole world would wake up
and go, "What's that?"

38:49.805 --> 38:53.853
It's Betty Broderick
going over the edge.

38:53.896 --> 38:56.812
[suspenseful music]

38:56.856 --> 39:03.428
♪

39:03.471 --> 39:06.344
But, you know,
nice girls don't do that.

39:06.387 --> 39:09.825
♪

39:09.869 --> 39:14.264
So I just
did the scream inside.

39:17.920 --> 39:20.183
[phone rings]

39:20.227 --> 39:22.055
- Hello?

39:22.098 --> 39:24.840
Hello?

39:24.884 --> 39:28.366
Slow down.
I can't understand you.

39:28.409 --> 39:29.454
You did what?

39:29.497 --> 39:31.804
[phone rings]

39:33.458 --> 39:35.634
- Hello?

39:35.677 --> 39:37.070
Was that you calling before?

39:37.113 --> 39:40.465
I'm sorry I didn't pick up.
I'm just so tired, I--

39:40.508 --> 39:41.509
What?

39:41.553 --> 39:44.599
- Who is this?

39:44.643 --> 39:47.602
Who is this?
You're scaring me.

39:47.646 --> 39:48.734
Betty?

39:48.777 --> 39:51.650
- What's the matter?

39:51.693 --> 39:54.217
Can you stop crying?
I-I can't...

39:54.261 --> 39:55.436
What happened?

39:55.480 --> 39:57.003
- The cops didn't know
anything about it.

39:57.046 --> 39:59.179
They couldn't even
really understand--

39:59.222 --> 40:01.007
Yeah,
I'm just gonna go over there.

40:01.050 --> 40:03.662
Yeah. Just check.
See what's going on.

40:03.705 --> 40:05.011
Some sort of prank.

40:05.054 --> 40:08.362
- Sh-she said
she doesn't know.

40:08.406 --> 40:10.408
[shaky breath] She said
it was completely dark,

40:10.451 --> 40:12.758
and she said
that he was talking to her.

40:12.801 --> 40:15.717
[line trilling]

40:18.981 --> 40:21.593
- Hi, we're back,
all tanned and rested.

40:21.636 --> 40:23.551
Please leave us a message.

40:23.595 --> 40:25.553
[beep]

40:25.597 --> 40:28.643
- Betty Anne.
Betty Anne.

40:28.687 --> 40:31.646
Are you still there?

40:31.690 --> 40:34.649
[dramatic music]

40:34.693 --> 40:38.784
♪

40:51.753 --> 40:55.496
- We still--I mean,

40:55.540 --> 40:58.412
no matter what...

40:58.456 --> 41:01.633
you went into Dan's house
and fired a gun.

41:01.676 --> 41:05.201
And we don't know if he...

41:05.245 --> 41:10.293
But I think regardless,
we need...

41:13.514 --> 41:16.561
Turn yourself in.

41:16.604 --> 41:19.215
Okay?
We need a lawyer.

41:19.259 --> 41:22.349
To find a lawyer,
criminal lawyer.

41:22.392 --> 41:26.048
Someone who'll come in
on a Sunday...

41:26.092 --> 41:28.311
to help you through the...

41:28.355 --> 41:30.749
with the police.

41:30.792 --> 41:33.752
[unsettling music]

41:33.795 --> 41:40.933
♪

42:08.177 --> 42:09.614
- Hi.

42:09.657 --> 42:11.790
Uh...

42:11.833 --> 42:14.140
I'm Matt Carpenter.

42:14.183 --> 42:16.795
Um...
we should probably get going.

42:16.838 --> 42:20.929
It was just, um...

42:20.973 --> 42:25.238
they're--they're both, um...

42:25.281 --> 42:27.457
yeah, it was on the radio.

42:32.811 --> 42:35.030
- This is number four
on the arraignment calendar,

42:35.074 --> 42:36.902
docket ending 646.

42:36.945 --> 42:38.338
The People of the State
of California

42:38.381 --> 42:39.818
versus
Elisabeth Anne Broderick.

42:39.861 --> 42:40.993
[taps gavel twice]

42:41.036 --> 42:43.082
- Good morning, everyone.

42:43.125 --> 42:45.084
Mrs. Broderick
is charged with two counts

42:45.127 --> 42:47.173
of first-degree murder.

42:47.216 --> 42:48.870
Mr. Carpenter,
how does your client plead?

42:48.914 --> 42:50.655
- We enter a plea
of not guilty, Your Honor,

42:50.698 --> 42:52.526
and request a jury trial.

42:52.570 --> 42:53.962
- Your Honor, as to bail,

42:54.006 --> 42:56.443
the defendant stole keys,
illegally entered,

42:56.486 --> 42:57.836
and given the severity
of the charges--

42:57.879 --> 43:00.186
- Mr. Norris, no need.

43:00.229 --> 43:01.753
Given the seriousness
of the charges,

43:01.796 --> 43:04.016
the defendant is remanded.

43:04.059 --> 43:06.627
Motions will be heard
on the 28th.

43:06.671 --> 43:08.107
[gavel taps]

43:08.150 --> 43:11.066
[soft, somber music]

43:11.110 --> 43:12.851
♪

43:12.894 --> 43:14.200
[metal clanks]

43:14.243 --> 43:16.637
[metallic clinking]

43:16.681 --> 43:19.466
[background chatter]

43:19.509 --> 43:22.600
[muffled, distant
PA announcement]

43:26.429 --> 43:28.910
[buzzer]

43:28.954 --> 43:32.871
[soft, somber music
continues]

43:32.914 --> 43:34.960
[dramatic musical sting]

43:35.003 --> 43:42.097
♪
